        <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0c/Mars_-_August_30_2021_-_Flickr_-_Kevin_M._Gill.png/435px-Mars_-_August_30_2021_-_Flickr_-_Kevin_M._Gill.png" width="560"> <!--This is the main picture you see right under the table of contents-->
        
        <h2 id = "MBF">Mars Basic Facts</h2>
        <p>Mars is the fourth planet from the sun, between Earth and the asteroid belt.</p>
        <p>Mars is called 'the red planet', coming from the thick red color of the surface. This is caused by rust coating the entire surface of Mars.</p>
        <p>Mars is a fourth the size of Earth and is much colder. The lows on Mars are −160 °F degrees!</p>
        <p>Mars has two moons, Phobos and Deimos. Phobos is bigger than and closer to Mars than Deimos is.</p>
        <p>Olympus Mons, a Martian mountain, is the biggest mountain known to mand kind. Nothing we know taller than Olympus Mons.</p>
        <p>Despite what it looks like now, Mars used to be bursting with life at one point. It had CO2, H2O, and even O2!</p>
        <p>Being the interesting planet it is, Mars has been visited by many space companies, including ESA & NASA!</p>
        
        </div>
        <div id= "Too-simple">
        
        <h2 id = "BMS">Basic Mars Statistics</h2>
        <p>Age: 4.6 BYA</p>
        <p>Mass: 1/10 Earths'</p>
        <p>Volume: 1/6 Earths'</p>
        <p>Axis tilt: 25°</p>
        <p>Distance from the sun: </p>
        <p>Temp max: 95 °F</p>
        <p>Temp min: −160 °F</p>
        <p>Moons: 2</p>
        <p>Gravity: 1/3 Earths'</p>
        
        </div>
        <div id= "Boring-piece">
        
        <h2 id = "MH">Martian History</h2>
        <p>Mars has been around for about 4.6 BILLION years, while Earth has been around for about 4.5 (Mars: 4.56 Earth: 4.47). Being almost 100 million years older than Earth, Mars has a lot more history for scientists to discover. So far, we know that water and oxygen were on Mars a <em>long</em> time ago. </p>
        <p>Mars was discovered in Medieval Roman times (Hence the name 'Mars', after the Roman god of war). The first time Mars was observed with a telescope was in <em>1620</em> by Galileo!</p>
        <p>About 4 billion years ago (Earth was still a baby), there was life and water on Mars! Because of the water on the planet, there are big valleys where martian seas were, mostly to the north, where the poles are (which also contain water!). (See Water on Mars)</p>
        <p></p>
        <p></p>
        <p></p>
        <p></p>
        <p></p>
        <p></p>
        
