        <h2 id = "MG">Martian Geography</h2>
        <p>Contents:</p>
    <p><a href = "##Olympus">Olympus Mons</a></p>
    <p></p>
    <p><a href = "##Tharis">Tharis Montes</a></p>
    <p></p>
        <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/94/Mars_MOLA_Topography_by_Fabio_Crameri.png" width="560">
        <p>Topography of Mars.<br><a href= "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Areography">Picture credit: Wikipedia <br></a></p>
        <h3 id = "#Olympus">Olympus Mons</h3>
        <p>Olympus Mons is the tallest mountain in the solar system. Being 21,230 meters tall, Olympus Mons is 3 times as tall as Mount Everest and 2 times as tall as Muana Kea! Being a shield volcano, it's also one of the widest mountains, too. Olympus Mons is the size of Poland!</p>
        <h3 id = "#Tharis">Tharsis Montes</h3>
        <p>Tharsis Montes is a mountain range on Mars that contains three mountains located in the tharsis region. (From north to south) The Mountains are Ascraeus Mons (18 km), Pavonis Mons (14 km), and Arsia Mons (20 km).</p>
        
        </div>
        
        <h2 id = "WOM">Water On Mars</h2>
        <img id = "WOM2" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/98/AncientMars.jpg/1024px-AncientMars.jpg" width="450">
        
        <p>Scientists already know water's been on Mars's surface before, they just don't know <em>exactly</em> how long it's been. The picture above (<a href= "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Water_on_Mars">Provided by Wikipedia</a>) shows what Mars probably looked like with water. The image below (<a href= "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Water_on_Mars">Also provided by Wikipedia</a>) shows a vague history of Mars in billions of years.</p>
        <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/a/a9/History_of_Water_on_Mars.jpg" width="450">
        <p>Valles Marineris used to be a river (hence the latin name 'Mariner's Valley'), but after all of Mars's surface water disappeared, the only thing left was the riverbed. (See image below <a href= "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Valles_Marineris">provided by Wikipedia</a>)</p>
         <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/92/VallesMarinerisHuge.jpg/1200px-VallesMarinerisHuge.jpg" width="560">
        
        <p><br></p>
        
        <!--This is the good part-->
        
        <h2 id = "TM">Terraforming Mars</h2>
        <p>Now that you know some good geography and history, let's talk about terraforming Mars. Terraforming Mars may seem like a really good idea, but it would take <em>tons</em> of resources, money, effort, and most of all, <em>time.</em></p>
        <p>To start off, Mars is on the <em>literal edge</em> of the habitable zone. (Shown below)</p>
        <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f0/Diagram_of_different_habitable_zone_regions_by_Chester_Harman.jpg/1920px-Diagram_of_different_habitable_zone_regions_by_Chester_Harman.jpg" width="560">
        <p>As this picture shows (<a href= "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Habitable_zone">Provided by Wikipedia</a>), Mars gets around 30% the amount of sunlight that Earth gets. Because of this, Mars is <strong>a lot</strong> colder than Earth, at around <em>225 degrees Fahrenheit!</em></p>
        <p></p>
        <p></p>
        
        <p><br></p>
        
